Of course, I know that I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, because comments directed at me tend to be only political.
I admire the professionalism and determination of colleagues who face the thunder of sexist or racist attacks every day and never hide from it.
One of the biggest disappointments of this political era is how the level of attacks has normalized.
Jeremy Corbyn argued last week that the Labour Party should promote a culture of tolerance.
In fact, we are no longer those notorious liberals, and with every stimulus to express “mistrust” or change the selection rules, the party becomes increasingly narrow.
Over the past two years, a lot of people have advised me not to stand out too much from the crowd, be quiet and keep up, and then I’ll be “all right.”
But I didn’t go into politics for that.
Ever since I joined the Labour Party as a student 32 years ago, provoked by the indifference of Thatcher’s government to allow my high school classroom to literally collapse, I’ve been trying to push for better public services for those who need it most – whether in the local council or in the ministry.
I never hid my politics, not even in the last election.
No one in the Nottingham East constituency could be confused by my political stances and areas of disagreement with the current leadership.
To those who supported the initiative on Friday, I would only say that when a country is creeping towards a Brexit that hurts households, businesses and our public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy to address my loyalty to the Labour leader.
But the main message that I have is not the vermin of the Momentum initiative in Nottingham. It is for the inhabitants of my district, whether they are members of the Labour Party or not: I am proud to have been able to serve you and I promise you that I am trying to make no threats of dismissal, I am not afraid of you for the sake of political calculus.
Chris Leslie is a member of Parliament for Nottingham East.
