'The sea is ours': Bolivia, cut off from the sea, hopes to regain access to the Pacific Ocean
The sailors besiege the naval headquarters in La Paz dressed in sails.
There are blue flags on public buildings.
Naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are shrouded in the motto: “The sea is our right.
Getting it back is our job.”
Throughout Bolivia, cut off from the sea, the memory of the coast lost to Chile in the bloody conflict of the 19th century is still alive – as is the desire to re-run the waters of the Pacific Ocean.
After five years of trial, Bolivia is awaiting the decision of the International Court of Justice on 1 October.
“Bolivia is on the rise, it has a spirit of unity and balance, and of course it believes in a positive outcome,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the international court’s ruling on big screens across the country in the hope that the Hague tribunal will decide in favor of Bolivia that, after decades of intermittent negotiations, Chile is obliged to negotiate for sovereign access to the sea to Bolivia.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president who will take part in the controversial re-election fight next year, also has something to say about Monday’s decision.
"Our return to the Pacific Ocean is within reach," he said at the end of August.
But some analysts believe it is unlikely that the court will rule in Bolivia’s favor – and even if it did, much would not have changed.
The UN body based in the Netherlands has no authority to allocate Chilean territory and said it would not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
The fact that the international court’s ruling comes just six months after hearing the final arguments suggests that the case “was not complicated,” said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And while there can be no doubt about Bolivia’s arguments, it is possible that it has taken a step backwards in recent years.
"The issue of access to the sea has been grasped by the current Bolivian government," Zárate said.
Morales’ aggressive rhetoric has undermined all of Chile’s remaining accommodatingness, she hinted.
Bolivia and Chile will one day resume negotiations, but after that it will be very difficult to maintain dialogue.
The two countries have not had an ambassadorial representation since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia’s deputy in The Hague, dismissed the idea that the court’s decision would be unusually swift.
Monday will bring Bolivia an “extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile” and a chance “to end 139 years of disagreement and achieve mutual benefits,” he said.
Calzadilla also dismissed the claim that Morales — still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents — would use the maritime question as a political barista.
“Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean,” he said.
“A decision is an opportunity to realize that we have to overcome the past.”
