John Edward: Without language skills, the global citizen cannot get away with it
Scottish independent schools maintain outstanding academic performance and this trend continues in 2018 with another year of outstanding exam scores, further strengthening individual and collective achievements in sports, arts, music and other social activities.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service to their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare pupils for further and higher education, careers according to their ideas and a place in the world as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement tailor-made curricula, we still perceive modern languages as a popular and sought-after elective subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “When you speak to a man in a language he understands, you speak to his head.
When you speak to him in his own language, you speak to his heart.”
It is a strong reminder that if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries, we cannot rely only on English.
From this year’s exam results, we can see that languages are at the top of the table with the highest average scores among independent schools.
In total, up to 68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved the highest A mark.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students achieved the highest A mark in Mandarin Chinese, 72 percent in German, 69 percent in French and 63 percent in Spanish.
This proves that independent schools in Scotland promote foreign languages as basic skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now considered to be as important as STEM (Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics) subjects in independent and other schools as elective subjects.
A 2014 survey by the UK’s Employment and Skills Commission found that 17% of the reasons employers cited as job recruitment problems were lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly essential in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more prospective jobs are created that require languages, these skills are becoming essential in a globalised world.
No matter what career a person chooses, as long as he has learned a second language, with such a lifelong ability he will have a real advantage for the future.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically give a multilingual person an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak any foreign language sufficiently to be able to communicate fluently, with French being the only language where the number of people reached double-digit percentages (15 percent).
Therefore, it is important for children today to invest in language learning.
Knowledge of multiple languages, especially those of advanced economies, will give children a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will be different according to the languages it teaches.
Some schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the UK in terms of the future in 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child is interested in, in independent schools he will always be able to choose from a variety of languages and will be taught by experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing an educational environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future may bring.
At present, it cannot be denied that, in the global business environment, languages remain crucial for the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should indeed be called "international communication abilities."
Independent schools will continue to offer this opportunity, diversity and excellent quality to young people in Scotland.
It's going to be fair.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
