North Korea will not unilaterally disarm without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the continued sanctions had deepened distrust of the United States and that the country would not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the world institution that North Korea has taken "substantial steps" over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site and committing not to expand nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"We do not see any response from the United States," he added.
“Without any confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances it is excluded that we will be the first to unilaterally disarm.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s opposition to a gradual approach to nuclear disarmament that would reward North Korea in taking step-by-step steps, his position was crucial in not immediately rejecting unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri cited a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the incumbent U.S. president and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work on “nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula” while Trump promised North Korea a security guarantee.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has declared that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also refused to release tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists first on nuclear disarmament and increases tensions through sanctions to achieve its purpose in a coercive way and even by objecting to a 'declaration to end the war,'" Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions will bring us to our knees is an illusion of people who know nothing about us.
The problem, however, is that the ongoing sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim Jong Un and Trump, which the U.S. president told the United Nations earlier this week.
But he stressed three meetings between Kim Jong Un and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the other side of the issue of nuclear disarmament were South Korea instead of the US, disarmament of the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a dead end.”
Yet the tone of Ri’s speech was dramatically different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting US territory with North Korean missiles was inevitable after “Mr. Evil” Trump called Kim a “missile man on a suicide mission.”
This year, Trump, who threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea last year, sang praise to Kim at the UN for his courage in taking disarmament steps, but said there was still a lot of work ahead of him and sanctions must remain until North Korea is de-nuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timetable for it, saying "it doesn't matter if it takes two, three years or five months."
China and Russia say the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “the sanctions imposed by the Security Council must continue rigorously and without exception until we achieve complete, final and verified nuclear disarmament.”
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in a bid to stifle funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri outside the UN General Assembly and said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go well.
In July, he left Pyongyang with the view that progress had been made, but hours later he was condemned by North Korea for making “gangster demands.”
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle the missile test site and the nuclear complex if the United States takes “appropriate measures.”
Kim told him that the “corresponding measures” he expected were the security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore and steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to relax enough
The goal of this year’s new course at Harvard University is to ensure that all students get more sleep in an effort to suppress the growing trend of studying all night long with the help of caffeine.
Researchers have found that students at the world’s leading university are often clueless when it comes to the complete basics of caring for their health.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at the Brigham and Women's Clinic, has developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after a lecture he gave about sleep deprivation and its impact on learning.
“At the end, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I only learning about this now, in my senior year?’
She claimed that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” she told The Telegraph.
This year’s first course explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance while improving overall health.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health service, said the university decided to open the course when it found that students suffered severe sleep deprivation during the work week.
The course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a screenshot of a boarding school where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, and books, and learn about the effects of caffeine, light, and how lack of sleep affects sports performance, and how important a regular sleep regimen is.
In the next section, participants will learn how long-term sleep deficiency can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The campus map with interactive icons further encourages participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know that this will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know – just as everyone has a right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” added Professor Czeisler.
There is still a culture in which students are proud to have been able to learn all night, he says, adding that modern technology and the growing pressure on students mean that sleep deprivation has become a growing problem.
Ensuring enough good quality sleep should be a “secret weapon” for students to fight stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said – even against weight gain, as sleep deficiency puts the brain into starvation mode, so they constantly feel hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his seminars last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to try to pursue the course at the university level.
He hopes that in the next step it will be possible to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before embarking on a challenging study.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set their alarm clocks for both the time to go to bed and the time to wake up, realizing the harmful effects of “blue light” that electronic screens and LED lighting emit, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, leading to trouble falling asleep.
