The Inventor of the Geiger Computer
And now we have a page from our Sunday morning chronicle: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago... that was the day the future physicist, Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the construction of a device known as the Geiger computer.
Geiger's computer, in addition to being an integral part of science to this day, also became a staple of pop culture when it was talked about in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado" by science-smelling cowboys Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: "What the hell is this?"
Rogers: “It’s a Geiger computer, it detects radioactive minerals, like uranium.
When you put on the headphones, you can actually hear the sounds of atoms that are produced by the radioactivity in the minerals.”
Evans: "Really, I can hear them cracking!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name lives on.
