Current status of red sludge: Concentrations drop in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission shows a general drop in red sludge concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Florida Commission, in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, uneven conditions have been reported in connection with the coating, suggesting declining concentrations.
Red mud extends approximately 130 miles of coastline from northern Pinellas to southern Lee districts.
The spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast in the Hillsborough area, but on fewer sites compared to last week.
Red mud was also spotted in the Pasco area.
Medium concentrations on or off the coast in the Pinellas area were reported last week, low to high sea concentrations in the Hillsborough area, high concentrations in the Manatee area, high concentrations on or off the coast in the Sarasota area, medium concentrations in the Charlotte area, high concentrations on or off the coast in the Lee area, and low concentrations in the Collier area.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier areas.
Respiratory irritation has not been reported in northwest Florida for the past week.
